# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alphonse-pinart
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Most of the islands belong to the U.S. state of Alaska, with the archipelago encompassing the Aleutians West Census Area and the Aleutians East Borough.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Commander Islands, located further to the west, belong to the Russian federal subject of Kamchatka Krai, of the Russian Far East.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Crossing longitude 180°, at which point east and west longitude end, the archipelago contains both the westernmost and easternmost parts of the United States, by longitude (Amatignak Island and Semisopochnoi Island, respectively).
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The westernmost U.S. island, in real terms, however, is Attu Island, west of which runs the International Date Line.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The islands, with their 57 volcanoes, form the northernmost part of the Pacific Ring of Fire.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Physiographically, they are a distinct section of the larger Pacific Border province, which, in turn, is part of the larger Pacific Mountain System physiographic division.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The islands are considered to be among the most geographically isolated areas of the Northern Pacific.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Battles and skirmishes took place during the Aleutian Islands campaign of World War II.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Japanese landing and occupations of Kiska and Attu, in June 1942, were one of only two invasions of the United States in North America during WWII; the Philippines, Guam and Wake Atoll, Pacific territories of the United States, were also invaded.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Motion between the Kula Plate and the North American Plate along the margin of the Bering Shelf (in the Bering Sea north of the Aleutian arc) ended in the early Eocene.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Basin, the ocean floor north of the Aleutian arc, is the remainder of the Kula Plate that was trapped when volcanism and subduction jumped south to its current location at c.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian island arc formed in the Early Eocene (55–50 Ma) when the subduction of the Pacific Plate under the North American Plate began.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The arc is made of separate blocks that have been rotated clockwise.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The basement underlying the islands is made of three stratigraphic units: an Eocene layer of volcanic rock, an Oligocene–Miocene layer of marine sedimentary rock, and a Pliocene–Quaternary layer of sedimentary and igneous rock.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] All six are located between 51° and 55° N latitude and 172° E and 163° W longitude.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The largest islands in the Aleutians are Attu, and Unalaska, Umnak, and Unimak in the Fox Islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The largest of those is Unimak Island, with an area of 1,571.41 mi2 (4,069.9 km2), followed by Unalaska Island, the only other Aleutian Island with an area over 1,000 square miles (2,600 km2).
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The axis of the archipelago near the mainland of Alaska has a southwest trend, but at Tanaga Island (about 178° W) its direction changes to the northwest.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] This change of direction corresponds to a curve in the line of volcanic fissures that have contributed their products to the building of the islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Such curved chains are repeated about the Pacific Ocean in the Kuril Islands, the Japanese chain, and in the Philippines.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] All these island arcs are at the edge of the Pacific Plate and experience much seismic activity, but are still habitable; the Aleutians lie between the Pacific and North American tectonic plates.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The general elevation is greatest in the eastern islands and least in the western.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The island chain is a western continuation of the Aleutian Range on the mainland.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The great majority of the islands bear evident marks of volcanic origin, and there are numerous volcanic cones on the north side of the chain, some of them active; many of the islands, however, are not wholly volcanic, but contain crystalline or sedimentary rocks, and also amber and beds of lignite.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The coasts are rocky and surf-worn, and the approaches are exceedingly dangerous, the land rising immediately from the coasts to steep, bold mountains.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] These volcanic islands reach heights of 6,200 feet (1,900 m).
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Makushin Volcano (5,691 feet (1,735 m)) on Unalaska Island, is not quite visible from within the town of Unalaska, though the steam rising from its cone is visible on a (rare) clear day.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Residents of Unalaska need only to climb one of the smaller hills in the area, such as Pyramid Peak or Mt.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Newhall, to get a good look at the snow-covered cone.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The volcanic Bogoslof and Fire Islands, which rose from the sea in 1796 and 1883 respectively, lie about 30 miles (50 km) west of Unalaska Bay.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In 1906, a new volcanic cone rose between the islets of Bogoslof and Grewingk, near Unalaska, followed by another in 1907.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] These cones were nearly demolished by an explosive eruption on September 1, 1907.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In 2017, the volcanic cone erupted sending ash and ice particles 30,000 feet (9000 m) into the air.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Alfred Russel Wallace's 1879 book *Australasia*, Ian Todd's 1974 book *Island Realm: A Pacific Panorama* and Dean Kohlhoff's 2002 book *Amchitka and the Bomb: Nuclear Testing in Alaska* all associate the Aleutian Islands with the Oceania region due to their status as remote islands in the Pacific.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The islands, having biogeographical and ethnocultural affinities to North America, are not ordinarily considered a part of the region.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The climate of the islands is oceanic, with moderate and fairly uniform temperatures and heavy rainfall.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Summer weather is much cooler than Southeast Alaska (around Sitka), but the winter temperature of the islands and of the Alaska Panhandle is nearly the same.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] To the northeast of that point, the climate becomes "Subarctic With Cool Summers And Year Around Rainfall" (type "Dfc", like Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky, Murmansk, St.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Moritz, and Labrador City), where it is similar albeit colder, with the coldest month averaging below 0 °C (32 °F).
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] During the winter, the islands become the center of a semi-permanent low-pressure area called the Aleutian Low.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The mean annual temperature for Unalaska, the most populated island of the group, is about 38 °F (3 °C), being about 30 °F (−1 °C) in January and about 52 °F (11 °C) in August.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The highest and lowest temperatures recorded on the islands were 78 °F (26 °C) and 5 °F (−15 °C), respectively.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The average amount of annual rainfall is about 80 inches (2,000 mm); Unalaska, with about 250 rainy days per year, is said to be one of the rainiest places within the U.S.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The growing season lasts approximately 135 days, from early in May until late in September, but agriculture is limited to the raising of few vegetables.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] With the exception of some stunted willows, the vast majority of the chain is devoid of native trees.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] On some of the islands, such as Adak and Amaknak, there are a few coniferous trees growing, remnants of the Russian period.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] While tall trees grow in many cold climates, Aleutian conifers — some estimated to be two hundred years old — rarely reach a height of even 10 feet (3 m), and many of them are still less than 5 feet (1.5 m) tall.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] This is because the islands, much like the Falklands and other islands of similar latitudes, experience such strong winds that taller trees are vulnerable to snapping off.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Instead of trees, the islands are covered with a luxuriant, dense growth of herbage and shrubs, including crowberry, bluejoint, grasses, sedges, and many flowering plants.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] There are areas of peat bog near the coasts.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Endemic plants include the endangered Aleutian shield fern.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] There is currently almost no naturally occurring forest in the Aleutian Islands, except with the help of human intervention.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] For example, the “Adak National Forest” on Adak Island is a man-made tree group consisting of 33 trees.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutians are home to many large colonies of seabirds.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Buldir Island has 21 breeding seabird species, including the Bering Sea-endemic red-legged kittiwake.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Large seabird colonies are also present at Kiska, Gareloi, Semisopochnoi, Bogoslof, and others.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The islands are also frequented by vagrant Asiatic birds, including the common rosefinch, Siberian rubythroat, bluethroat, lanceolated warbler, and the first North American record of the intermediate egret.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The habitats of the Aleutians are largely unspoiled, but wildlife is affected by competition from introduced species such as cattle, caribou, and foxes.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Nearly all of the Aleutians are protected as part of the Alaska Maritime National Wildlife Refuge and the Aleutian Islands Wilderness.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Observations have identified sea otters as a keystone species along the coasts of many of the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Their presence encourages the growth of kelp forests, as the otters control sea urchin populations (as large populations of sea urchins can create urchin barrens by clearing away kelp stands).
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The native people refer to themselves as Unangan, and are now generally known by most non-natives as the Aleut.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleut language is one of the two main branches of the Eskimo–Aleut language family.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] This family is not known to be related to any others.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The 2020 U.S. census recorded a population of 7,152 on the islands, of whom 4,254 were living in the main settlement of Unalaska.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] On the less mountainous islands, the raising of sheep and reindeer was once believed to be practicable.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] There are bison on islands near Sand Point.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Sheep raising seems to have died off with the advent of synthetic fibers, which lowered the value of wool.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] During the 1980s, there were some llama being raised on Unalaska.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The current economy is primarily based on fishing, and the presence of U.S. military.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Chickens are raised in barns under protection from the cold.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In addition to a partial air service and a ferry service, the Alaska Marine Highway passes through many of the U.S. islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Because the islands stretch like a broken bridge from the continent Asia to the continent North America, many anthropologists hypothesize they were a route of the first human occupants of the Americas.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] However, the earliest known evidence in public recorded history of human occupation in the Americas is found much farther south.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The early human sites in the Bering Sea were probably submerged by rising waters and sand during the current interglacial period.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] People living in or on the Aleutian Islands developed skills in hunting, fishing, and basketry.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The baskets were woven with shredded stalks of beach rye.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Explorers, traders and missionaries arrived from Russia beginning in 1741.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In 1741 the Russian government sent Vitus Bering, a Danish-born Russian, and Aleksei Chirikov, a Russian, in the ships *Saint Peter* and *Saint Paul* on a voyage of discovery in the Northern Pacific.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] After the ships were separated by a storm; Chirikov discovered several eastern islands of the Aleutian group, and Bering discovered several of the western islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Bering was shipwrecked and died in the Komandorski Islands (Commander Islands); one of which now bears his name (Bering Island), along with the surrounding Bering Sea.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The survivors of Bering's party reached the Kamchatka Peninsula in a boat constructed from the wreckage of their ship, and reported the islands were rich in fur-bearing animals.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Siberian fur hunters flocked to the Commander Islands and gradually moved eastward across the Aleutian Islands to North America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In this manner, Russia gained a foothold on the northwestern coast of North America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Islands consequently belonged to Russia, until that country transferred all its possessions in North America to the U.S. in the 1867 Alaska Purchase.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The colonies soon entered a relatively stable state based on cooperation, intermarriage, and official policies that provided social status, education, and professional training to children of mixed Aleut-Russian birth.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Within a generation, the day-to-day administration of the Russian-American colonies was largely in the hands of native-born Alaskans.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Reversing the usual trend in colonization where indigenous technologies are replaced, the Russians adopted the Aleut kayak, or baidarka, sea otter hunting techniques, and the working of native copper deposits.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] By 1760 the Russian merchant Andrian Tolstykh had made a detailed census in the vicinity of Adak and extended Russian citizenship to the Aleuts.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] During his third and last voyage in 1778, Captain James Cook surveyed the eastern portion of the Aleutian archipelago, accurately determined the position of some of the more important islands, and corrected many errors of former navigators.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Among the first Christian missionaries to arrive in the Aleutian Islands was a party of ten Russian Orthodox monks and priests, who arrived in 1793.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Within two years, a monk named Herman was the only survivor of that party.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] He settled on Spruce Island, near Kodiak Island, and often defended the rights of the Aleuts against the Russian trading companies.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] He is now known in the Orthodox Church as Saint Herman of Alaska.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Another early Christian missionary of the Russian Orthodox Church was Father Veniaminov who arrived in Unalaska in 1824.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] He was named Bishop Innokentii in 1840 and moved to Sitka.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] He is now known in the Orthodox Church as Saint Innocent of Alaska.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The principal settlements were on Unalaska Island.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The oldest was Iliuliuk (also called Unalaska), settled in 1760–1775, with a customs house and an Orthodox church.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] After the American purchase of Alaska from Russia in 1867, further development took place.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] New buildings included a Methodist mission and orphanage, and the headquarters for a considerable fleet of United States revenue cutters, which patrolled the sealing grounds of the Pribilof Islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The first public school in Unalaska opened in 1883.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Congress extended American citizenship to all Native Americans in 1924; this law has been held to include the indigenous peoples of Alaska.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] A hospital was built in Unalaska in 1933 by the U.S.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] Navy, having broken the Japanese naval codes, proceeded as if this was just a diversion, and it did not expend large amounts of effort in defending the islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] More than 90 Americans were taken to Japan as prisoners of war.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The United States moved most of the remaining civilian population (over 800) of the Aleutians and Pribilovians to camps in the Alaska Panhandle.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In May 1943, American forces invaded Japanese-held Attu and defeated the Japanese.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In August 1943, American and Canadian troops launched an invasion of Kiska, in which 34,426 men composed of both Americans and Canadian participated; however, Japanese forces had already evacuated the island, ending the campaign in the islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] President Roosevelt visited Adak in 1944, meeting with commanders and eating with soldiers of the garrison.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] This was his first and only trip to the Aleutian Islands and Alaska as a whole.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] A rumor spread that FDR had accidentally left his Scottish Terrier "Fala" on one of the Islands and had to send a destroyer to retrieve the dog, costing taxpayers several million dollars.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The President made fun of these rumors during a talk with the Teamsters Union in Washington DC, now known as the "Fala Speech".
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] June 3, 2002, was celebrated as Dutch Harbor Remembrance Day.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The governor of Alaska ordered state flags lowered to half-staff to honor the 43 Americans who died during the two-day Japanese air attack in 1942.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian World War II National Historic Area Visitors Center opened that month.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The U.S. conducted underground tests of nuclear weapons on Amchitka Island from 1965 to 1971 as part of the Vela Uniform program.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The final detonation, the Cannikin, was the largest underground nuclear explosion by the U.S.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Alaska Native Claims Settlement Act became law in 1971.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] In 1977, the Ounalashka Corporation (from Unalaska) declared a dividend.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] This was the first village corporation to declare and pay a dividend to its shareholders.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutian Islands were designated a UNESCO biosphere reserve in 1976.
[src:alphonse-pinart/aleutian-islands] The Aleutians were one of 17 biosphere reserves in the United States withdrawn by request of the U.S. government from the programme in June 2017.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] The son of a wealthy forge master, a learned young man who had learned English, Russian and some Asian linguistics with Stanislas Julien, he was fascinated by the age of 15 for the question of the origin of the Amerindians and Inuit.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] The meeting of the Abbé Brasseur de Bourbourg at the International Exposition of 1867 in Paris decided Pinart‘a vocation.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He conceived the project of going to Alaska to study native languages in order to prove the Siberian origin of the Amerindians; at the time, this idea had few supporters.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He may also have been interested in archeology by the discovery in 1864 in Équihen, by workers of the family business, human skeletons, and antique objects.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Another likely influence is anthropologist Ernest Hamy, a 10-year-old fellow, with whom Pinart would remain linked to.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] The latter, first curator of the Ethnographic Museum of Trocadero and director of scientific missions from 1880, would later appeal to him.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] At 19, Pinart realized his project of travel at his expense; he resided from spring 1871 to spring 1872 in Alaska, a region that has just been acquired by the United States after nearly a century of Russian occupation, and made a visit to the Aleutian Islands.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He returned to France with sixty masks from the Kodiak archipelago and eight others discovered in a burial cave Akhanh on the island of Unga (Aleutian Islands).
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Chauvet3, his youth and energy allow him to perform sports such as the solitary kayak trip from Unalaska to Kodiak, which facilitates the search for objects and impresses the locals.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Between 1873 and 1874, he traveled to Russia, namely St.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Petersburg and Moscow, but also to Copenhagen, Helsinki, and Tartu, to copy additional documentation on the peoples of the Bering Strait, partly for himself, in commissioned part of the American historian George Bancroft (1832-1918).
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He is one of the many assistants Bancroft relied on for writing his History of America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Pinart would build a collection of documents and manuscripts and bequeath to him personal documents.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Shortly after his return to France, he left for America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] In 1875 and 1876 he visited Maine, Nova Scotia, Oregon, British Columbia, Washington State, and Arizona.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] In the meantime, in 1875, he acquired from the antique dealer Eugene Boban a large collection of Mesoamerican coins.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He knew his first financial problems because, besides the expenses of the expedition of 1871-1872, he bought a good part of the library of Brasseur de Bourbourg.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] In 1879, Eugene Boban complained of not having received all of his due and the funds wete missing to continue his explorations.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] Alphonse Pinart then negotiated with the Ministry of Education the financing of his expedition (granted 2 April 1878) jointly with Leon de Cessac, against the donation of his collection to the Museum of Ethnography Trocadero.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] In 1874, Pinart received for his trip to Alaska and the Strait of Bering the Gold Medal for study tour, missions and reconnaissance works of the Geographical Society, and in 1875, a medal of the International Geographical Union at the Paris Congress.
[src:alphonse-pinart/alphonse-pinart] He would receive another in 1877 from the Acclimatization Society.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boisdinghem] A small village situated 5 miles (8 km) west of Saint-Omer, on the D206 road.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne is an ancient town and was the main Roman port for trade and communication with its Province of Britain.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] After a period of Germanic presence following the collapse of the Empire, Boulogne was integrated into the County of Boulogne of the Kingdom of France during the Middle Ages.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It was occupied by the Kingdom of England numerous times due to conflict between the two nations.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 1805 it was a staging area for Napoleon's troops for several months during his planned invasion of the United Kingdom.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The city's 12th-century belfry is recognised by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site (along with other belfries of Belgium and France), while another popular attraction is the marine conservation centre Nausicaa.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The French name *Boulogne* derives from the Latin *Bononia*, which was also the Roman name for Bologna in Italy.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Both places – and Vindobona (Vienna) – are thought to have derived from native Celtic placenames, with *bona* possibly meaning "foundation", "citadel", or "granary".
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The French epithet *sur-Mer* ("on sea") distinguishes the city from Boulogne-Billancourt on the edge of Paris.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In turn, the *Boulogne* in Boulogne-Billancourt originates from a church there dedicated to Notre-Dame de Boulogne, "Our Lady of Boulogne[-sur-Mer]".
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The foundation of the city known to the Romans as **Gesoriacum** is credited to the Celtic Boii.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In the past, it was sometimes conflated with Caesar's Portus Itius, but that is now thought to have been a site near Calais which has since silted up.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] A tall lighthouse was built at Gesoriacum circa 39 AD by order of the Emperor Caligula, possibly in preparation for an invasion of Britain.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Known as the Tour d'Ordre, coastal erosion caused it to topple into the sea in 1644.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] From the time of Claudius's invasion in AD 43, Gesoriacum formed the major port connecting the rest of the empire to Britain.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It was the chief base of the Roman navy's Britannic fleet until the rebellion of its admiral Carausius in 286.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] As part of the imperial response, the junior emperor Constantius Chlorus successfully besieged it by land and sea in 293.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The name of the settlement was changed to **Bononia** at some point between the sack of Gesoriacum and 310, possibly as a consequence of its refounding or possibly by the replacement of the sacked and lower-lying city by another nearby community.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The city was an important town of the Morini (the 'sea people'), and Zosimus called it *Germanorum* ("Germanic-speaking") at the end of the 4th century.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In the Middle Ages Boulogne was the capital of an eponymous county, founded in the mid-9th century.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] An important Count, Eustace II, assisted William the Conqueror in his conquest of England.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] His wife founded the city's Notre Dame cathedral, which became a site of pilgrimage from the 12th century onwards, attended by fourteen French kings and five of England.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It was an important whaling center prior to 1121.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The city survived on herring fishing and received its municipal charter from Count Renaud of Dammartin in 1203.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The area was fought over by the French and the English, including several English occupations during the course of the Hundred Years War.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 1492 Henry VII laid siege to Boulogne before the conflict was ended by the Peace of Étaples.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne was again occupied by the English from 1544 to 1550.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 1550, The Peace of Boulogne ended the war of England with Scotland and France.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] France bought back Boulogne for 400,000 crowns.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] A culture of smuggling was present in the city until 1659, when French gains in Flanders from the Treaty of the Pyrenees moved the border northwards.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne received its current status as a subprefecture of the Pas-de-Calais department in 1800 due to the territorial re-organisation in Revolutionary France.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] France became the French Empire in 1804; in 1803 Boulogne became an Imperial City *(Ville Impériale)*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The 19th century was a prosperous one for Boulogne, which became a bathing resort for wealthy Parisians after the 1848 completion of the Longueau–Boulogne railway connecting the town with the French capital.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In the 19th century, the Basilica of Notre-Dame de Boulogne was reconstructed by the priest Benoît Haffreingue, who claimed to have received a call from God in 1820 to reconstruct the town's ruined basilica.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] During the Napoleonic Wars, Napoleon amassed La Grande Armée in Boulogne to invade the United Kingdom in 1805.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] However, his plans were halted by other European matters and by the supremacy of the Royal Navy.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] A nephew of Napoleon Bonaparte, Louis-Napoleon Bonaparte (subsequently the emperor Napoleon III), returned to France in secret from his exile in Britain, passing through Boulogne in August 1840.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] He was later jailed for trying to lead a revolt in Strasbourg.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] During the First World War, this was the entrepôt for the first unit of the British Expeditionary Force to land in France and for many others thereafter.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne was one of the three base ports most extensively used by the Commonwealth armies on the Western Front throughout the First World War.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It was closed and cleared on 27 August 1914 when the Allies were forced to fall back ahead of the German advance, but was opened again in October and from that month to the end of the war, Boulogne and Wimereux formed one of the chief hospital areas.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Until June 1918, the dead from the hospitals at Boulogne were buried in the Cimetiere de L'Est, one of the town's cemeteries, the Commonwealth graves forming a long, narrow strip along the right hand edge of the cemetery.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In the spring of 1918, it was found that space was running short in the Eastern Cemetery in spite of repeated extensions to the south and the site of the new cemetery at Terlincthun was chosen.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It also was the site of an Allied (French and British) armaments production conference.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] On 22 May 1940 during the Battle of France, two British Guards battalions and some pioneers attempted to defend Boulogne against an attack by the German 2nd Panzer Division.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Despite fierce fighting, the British were overwhelmed and the survivors were evacuated by Royal Navy destroyers while under direct German gunfire.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] On 15 June 1944, 297 aircraft (155 Avro Lancasters, 130 Handley Page Halifaxes, and 12 De Havilland Mosquitos) of the Royal Air Force bombed Boulogne harbour to suppress German naval activity following D-Day.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Some of the Lancasters carried Tallboy bombs and the harbour and the surrounding area were completely destroyed.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In August 1944 the town was declared a "fortress" by Adolf Hitler but it succumbed to Operation Wellhit, the assault and liberation by the 3rd Canadian Infantry Division in September.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In one incident, a French civilian guided the Canadians to a "secret passage" leading into the walled old town and by-passing the German defenders.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] To replace the destroyed urban infrastructure, affordable housing and public facility projects in functional, brutalist building styles were carried out in the 1950s and 60s.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-sur-Mer is in Northern France, at the edge of the Channel and in the mouth of the river Liane.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In a direct line, Boulogne is approximately at 30 kilometres (19 miles) from Calais, 50 kilometres (31 miles) from Folkestone, 100 kilometres (62 miles) from Lille and Amiens, 150 kilometres (93 miles) from Rouen and London and 215 kilometres (134 miles) from Paris.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne is a relatively important city of the North, exercising an influence on the Boulonnais territory (74 towns and villages which surround Boulogne).
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The coast consists of important tourist natural sites, like the capes Gris Nez and Blanc Nez (which are the closest points of France to England), and attractive seaside resorts like Wimereux, Wissant, Hardelot and Le Touquet.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The hinterland is mainly rural and agricultural.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-sur-Mer has an oceanic climate that has chilly winters not far above freezing and cool summers tempered by its exposure to the sea.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Considering its position, the climate is quite cold in relation to south and east coast locations in England year round.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Due to warm winds originating inland, the record temperatures in summer are well above the averages and the warmest day of the year is averaging about 31 °C (88 °F).
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Summer diurnal temperature variation is low, with normals varying between nights of 15 °C (59 °F) with days at about 20 °C (68 °F).
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Precipitation is also higher than in said southern English locations.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Between 1981 and 2010 the precipitation days averaged 125.3 annually, although overall precipitation increased somewhat in the next averages of 1991 to 2020.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne is close to the A16 motorway (Paris-Amiens-Calais-Dunkerque).
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Metropolitan bus services are operated by "Marinéo".
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The company Flixbus proposed establishing a bus line connecting Paris to Boulogne.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] There are coach services to Calais and Dunkerque.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The city has several railway stations, of which the most important is Boulogne-Ville station, located in the south of the city.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-Tintelleries station is used by regional trains.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It is located near the university and the city centre.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The former Boulogne-Maritime and Boulogne-Aéroglisseurs stations served as a boat connection (to England) for the railway.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-Ville was the terminus of the Chemin de fer de Boulogne à Bonningues (CF de BB), which extended their line from Saint-Martin-Boulogne on 12 May 1902.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Within Boulogne were also halts at Rue de la Lampe, Rue de la Liane, Abbatoir and La Madelaine.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The CF de BB closed to passenger traffic on 31 December 1935.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It was reopened in November 1942, and closed in 1948.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The regional trains are TER Hauts-de-France run by SNCF.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The principal service runs from Gare de Boulogne-Ville via Gare de Calais-Fréthun, Gare de Calais-Ville to Gare de Lille-Flandres.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] From 2026, Hibernia Line will operate a ferry service to and from Cork, re-establishing a ferry operation in Boulogne following the closure of the route to Dover by LD Lines in 2010.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne's 12th-century belfry is one of 56 listed Belfries of Belgium and France, all in northeastern France and Belgium, with shared World Heritage Site status because of their architecture and testimony to the rise of municipal power in the region.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It is the oldest building in the upper city of Boulogne, and currently serves as the home to a museum of Celtic remains from the Roman occupation.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Founded as the Count's dungeon, the top floor was added in the 13th century.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Damage by a fire in 1712 was built over by 1734.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-sur-Mer is an important fishing port, with 7,000 inhabitants deriving part, or all, of their livelihoods from fishing.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] IFREMER (the French Research Institute for Exploitation of the Sea) and the Pasteur Institute are located in Boulogne Port.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Certain brands, including Crown and Findus, have regional offices in Boulogne.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 1905, the first World Esperanto Congress was held in Boulogne-sur-Mer, where the historic Declaration of Boulogne was ratified.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Zamenhof, the creator of Esperanto, was among the attendees.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 2005, there was an anniversary celebration to mark the centenary with more than 500 attendees.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] In 2022, 41,039 people lived in the commune, while its metropolitan area had a population of 159,973.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne-sur-Mer hosts one of the oldest *Universités de l'été* – summer courses in French language and culture.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] It is known as the Université d'été de Boulogne-sur-Mer.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The Saint-Louis building of the University of the Côte d'Opale's Boulogne campus opened its doors in 1991, on the site of the former St.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Louis Hospital, the front entrance to which remains a predominant architectural feature.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Its 6 major specialisms are Modern Languages, French Literature, Sport, Law, History and Economics.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The university is situated in the town centre, about 5 minutes from the Boulogne Tintelleries railway station.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Two health centres are located in Boulogne, the public Hospital Duchenne and the private Clinique de la côte d'opale.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne's football club, US Boulogne Côte d'Opale (US refers to Union Sportive), is one of the oldest in France due to the city's proximity to England, founded in 1898.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] The club currently play in the third tier, the Championnat National, and host home matches at the 14,500-capacity Stade de la Libération.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Boulogne native and FIFA World Cup finalist Franck Ribéry began his career at the club.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Basketball teams in Boulogne include Stade Olympique Maritime Boulonnais and ESSM Le Portel of Pro A (first-tier men's professional basketball league in France).
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] La Casa San Martin is currently a museum where José de San Martín the father of independence of Argentina (also Chile and Peru) died in 1850, from 1930 to 1967 this house was the consulate of Argentina in France.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] There is a statue dedicated to his colleague Simón Bolívar, other liberator of South America in the revolutions against Spanish colonial rule in the 1810s.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Bolivar planned to head in exile to this very part of France before his death in 1830.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Historic emigration in the 19th century from the Nord-Pas de Calais region to Argentina and Chile can explain some cultural ties with South America of the *Boulognais* and Latino/Ibero-American culture.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] Nausicaä, the French national sealife centre.
[src:alphonse-pinart/boulogne-sur-mer] As an international maritime port on the English Channel (*La Manche*), the town of Boulogne-sur-Mer has European and American influences in local cuisine.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Abbé **Charles-Étienne Brasseur de Bourbourg** (8 September 1814 – 8 January 1874) was a noted French writer, ethnographer, historian, archaeologist, and Catholic priest.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He became a specialist in Mesoamerican studies, travelling extensively in the region.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His writings, publications, and recovery of historical documents contributed much to knowledge of the region's languages, writing, history and culture, particularly those of the Maya and Aztec civilizations.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] However, his speculations concerning relationships between the ancient Maya and the lost continent of Atlantis inspired Ignatius L.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Donnelly and encouraged the pseudo-science of Mayanism.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He was born in Bourbourg, a small town with many Flemish influences near Dunkirk, France, as the First French Empire was ending.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] As a youth he went to Ghent in newly independent Belgium to study theology and philosophy.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He became interested in writing during his studies there.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Enthusiastic about Flanders' history, he wrote several essays about local folklore, which enabled him to enter literary circles.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1837, aged 23, Brasseur traveled to Paris with the support of French poet Alphonse-Marie-Louis de Prat Lamartine.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In Paris, he became involved with political newspapers that sought the democratization of power such as *Le Monde*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] During this time, he began contributing essays to a Parisian journal.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He wrote several historical accounts (using a pseudonym), including one concerning Jerusalem.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He published several novels of Romantic style which was then very much in vogue.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] One of these, *Le Sérapéon*, received reviews which implied it had a very close resemblance to François-René de Chateaubriand's 1809 novel *Les Martyrs*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Such near-allegations of plagiarism and inaccuracies in his works were to be made several times during his career.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Despite such criticisms, his reputation as a notable young writer and intellectual continued to develop.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He transferred his studies and residence to Rome, where in 1845 he was ordained into the Roman Catholic priesthood, at the age of 30.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] A year previously he had come to the attention of the Canadian Abbé, Léon Gingras, whom he had met (and apparently impressed) in Rome.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Abbé Gingras entreated his friend and colleague the vicar-general of Quebec, Abbé Charles-Félix Cazeau, to have Brasseur de Bourbourg assigned to a job in the seminary there.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Correspondence began in late 1844, with Abbé Gingras claiming that the seminary should *"...move heaven and earth to ensure that such a splendid bird does not escape us and fly to Montreal, where it would be so highly thought of"*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] A year later after having obtained his ordination, Brasseur de Bourbourg's job in Quebec was approved by the Archbishop, Joseph Signay, and in the autumn of 1845 he left Europe for the British colony of the Province of Canada, stopping briefly in Boston along the way.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Upon his arrival in Quebec City he began work as a professor of ecclesiastical history at the seminary (the Séminaire de Québec, founded in 1663).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] After only a brief time however, his series of lectures was discontinued, for some unspecified reason.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The results of his archival investigations were published in early 1846 as a biography of Laval.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The contents of this pamphlet seemed to displease his Canadian colleagues somewhat, for a dispute began which made his position there uncertain, or at least uncomfortable.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Also, he apparently disliked the harsh winter climate (to judge by some comments he made in the dedication of his later *History of Canada*), and may also have been a factor in his departure which was soon to ensue.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He left the seminary later in that year, returning to Boston where he found a job with the diocese of Boston.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The then current bishop, John Bernard Fitzpatrick, with whom he was evidently on better terms than with his previous superiors, made him vicar-general of the diocese.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Towards the end of the year Brasseur de Bourbourg returned to Europe, to spend some time conducting research in the archives of Rome and Madrid, in preparation for a new project—travel to Central America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] From 1848 to 1863 he travelled extensively as a missionary in many parts of Mexico and Central America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] During these journeys he gave great attention to Mesoamerican antiquities and became well-versed in the then-current theories and knowledge about the history of the region and the Pre-Columbian civilisations whose sites and monuments remained, yet were little understood.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He also conducted research into the local languages and their transliteration into the Latin alphabet.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Between 1861 and 1864 he edited and published a collection of documents in the indigenous languages.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1864 he was archaeologist of the French military expedition in Mexico, and his resulting work *Monuments anciens du Mexique* was published by the French Government in 1866.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1862 while searching through archives at the Royal Academy of History in Madrid for New World materials, he came across an abridged copy of a manuscript which had originally been written by the Spanish cleric Diego de Landa sometime around 1566.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] De Landa had been one of those charged with disseminating the Roman Catholic faith amongst the Maya peoples in Spain's new Central American possessions during the period after the Spanish conquest of Yucatán, and had lived there for several years.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His manuscript (*Relación de las Cosas de Yucatán*) had been written upon his enforced return to Spain, where he was charged with illegally or improperly conducting an Inquisition (he was later absolved, returning to the New World as the appointed Bishop of Yucatán).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In the manuscript de Landa had recorded much information about the Maya peoples and customs, based on his own observations and discussions with Mayan informants.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Brasseur de Bourbourg's main interest in the document, however, was a section in which de Landa reproduced what he termed "an alphabet" of the as-yet undeciphered Maya hieroglyphics, the writing system of the ancient Maya civilization.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In this passage de Landa had annotated the Mayan symbols (or glyphs) which supposedly corresponded to the letters of the Spanish alphabet, as given to him by a Maya informant who he had quizzed.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Brasseur de Bourbourg realised that this could prove to be basis of deciphering the Maya script, and he announced this discovery when republishing the manuscript (in a bilingual Spanish-French edition) in late 1863 with the title, *Relation des choses de Yucatán de Diego de Landa*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] However, upon initial analysis by Brasseur de Bourbourg and others, the so-called "de Landa alphabet" proved to be problematic and inconsistent, and these immediate attempts to use this alphabet as a kind of "Rosetta Stone" to read the glyphs failed.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Nevertheless, Brasseur de Bourbourg's uncovering of this document and de Landa's alphabet would much later prove to be vital in the eventual decipherment of the Maya glyphs.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Brasseur de Bourbourg's attempts, and those of others which followed, were misled insofar as they interpreted the signs alphabetically.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] When the signs were recognised to be mainly syllabic, significant progress was made.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1861 he published another significant work: a French translation of the Popol Vuh, a sacred book of the Quiché (Kʼicheʼ) Maya people.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He included a grammar of the Kʼicheʼ language and an essay on Central American mythology.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Brasseur began to write about Atlantis in his publication *Grammaire de la langue quichée* (1862), in which he expressed his belief that the lost land described by Plato had existed with an advanced degree of civilization before the beginning of civilizations in Europe and Asia.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He suggested that the origins of European and Persian words could be traced to indigenous languages of the Americas and that the ancient cultures of the New and Old Worlds had been in constant communication with one another.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1866, *Monuments anciens du Mexique (Palenque, et autres ruines de l'ancienne civilisation du Mexique)* was published with a text by Brasseur de Bourbourg accompanied by lavish illustrations by Jean-Frédéric Waldeck.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Although Waldeck's depictions of the ruins at Palenque were based on first-hand knowledge, his artistic reconstructions and embellishments implied a close relationship between Maya art and architecture and that of Classical antiquity Greece and Rome.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] This was subsequently demonstrated to be spurious, but not before Waldeck's artwork had inspired speculations about contact between New and Old World civilizations, specifically via the lost continent of Atlantis.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] These speculations were reinforced by Brasseur de Bourboug's own references to Plato's descriptions of the culture and society of Atlantis, which Brasseur believed was continued by ancient Maya civilization, in his book *Quatre Lettres sur le Méxique* (1868).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In this publication, Brasseur de Bourbourg made extensive parallels between Maya and Egyptian pantheons and cosmologies, implying that they all had a common source on the lost continent of Atlantis.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He developed these ideas further in his publication *Quatre lettres sur le Mexique* (1868), which presents a history of Atlantis based on his interpretation of Maya myths.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His writings inspired Augustus Le Plongeon and also Ignatius L.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Donnelly, whose book *Atlantis: The Antediluvian World* contains numerous references to Brasseur de Bourbourg's scholarship.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] However, an academic wrote in 1875 that not a single contemporary scholar accepted Brasseur de Bourbourg's theories about Atlantis.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The combination of Brasseur de Bourbourg's interests in spiritualism and these speculations about relations between the ancient Maya and Atlantis provided the basis for Mayanism.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1866, Brasseur de Bourbourg had an opportunity to examine an artefact in Madrid which was in the possession of a Spanish paleography professor named Juan de Tro y Ortolano, who had purchased it some six years earlier.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] This artefact was an old codex, a book made from paper-bark in the form of a folded screen of continuous pages, several metres in length when extended.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The codex contained numerous signs and drawings, which Brasseur de Bourbourg was readily able to identify as being Mayan in origin, having seen and studied many similar markings and glyphs while in Central America.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] Tro y Ortolano gave him permission to publish the codex in a reproduction, and Brasseur de Bourbourg gave it the name *Troano Codex* in his honour.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His identification of the codex was significant, as it was the only third such Maya codex to have been uncovered (the second, the Codex Paris, had been discovered by the French scholar Léon de Rosny only a few years before).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In particular, Brasseur de Bourbourg recognised its exceeding rarity, since de Landa's *Relación*, which he had earlier rediscovered, gave an account of how he had ordered the destruction of all such Maya codices he could find, and many volumes had been burned.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] During 1869–1870 Brasseur de Bourbourg published his analyses and interpretations of the content of the Troano codex in his work *Manuscrit Troano, études sur le système graphique et la langue des Mayas*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He proposed some translations for the glyphs recorded in the codex, in part based on the associated pictures and in part on de Landa's alphabet, but his efforts were tentative and largely unsuccessful.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] However, his translation would later inspire Augustus Le Plongeon's pseudo-science and speculation about the lost continent of Mu.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The name *Mu* was actually used first by Brasseur de Bourbourg.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] A few years later, another Maya codex was found possessed by another collector, which became known as the *Codex Cortesianus* (in the belief that it had been in the possession of Hernán Cortés).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] When Léon de Rosny examined it later, he determined that it was actually a part of the Troano codex, the two parts having been separated at some indeterminate time in the past.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The two parts were later rejoined and are known collectively as the Codex *Madrid* or *Tro-Cortesianus*; they remain displayed in Madrid.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] In 1871 Brasseur de Bourbourg published his *Bibliothèque Mexico-Guatémalienne*, a compendium of literature and sources associated with Mesoamerican studies.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His last article, "Chronologie historique des Mexicains" (1872) refers to the Codex Chimalpopoca and identifies four periods of world cataclysms that began about 10,500 BC and were the result of shifts of the Earth's axis (a concept related to pole shift theory).
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] He died at Nice at the beginning of 1874, at the age of 59.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] His archaeological fieldwork, as well as his diligent collection, discovery and republication of source materials, proved to be very useful for subsequent Mesoamerican researchers and scholars.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The interpretations and theories he advanced proved to be mostly inaccurate.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] A listing of his publications (either original works or reproductions of historical documents), by original publication date.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] The place of publication is annotated (in brackets), and the shorter or common name of the publication **is bolded**.
[src:alphonse-pinart/charles-étienne-brasseur-de-bourbourg] A collection of travel accounts and reports which Brasseur de Bourbourg sent to the French Minister for Education and Religion from Mexico, Guatemala and Spain is stored at the *Archives Nationales* (Paris), F17, 2942.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] He studied medicine in Paris, earning his doctorate in 1868.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] Afterwards, he served as a *préparateur* under Paul Broca in the laboratory of anthropology at the Ecole pratique des hautes études.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] In 1872 he became an assistant naturalist at the Muséum national d'histoire naturelle, where he worked closely with Armand de Quatrefages.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1891.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] In 1892 he was appointed professor of anthropology at the Museum.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] He was founder and curator of the Musée d'Ethnographie du Trocadéro as well as creator of the *Revue d’ethnographie*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] He was vice-president (1886) and president (1895) of the Société des traditions populaires, and a founding member of the Société des américanistes (1892).
[src:alphonse-pinart/ernest-hamy] Also, he was a member of the Société d’Anthropologie de Paris and the Société de géographie.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] Eyraud was born in Saint-Bonnet-en-Champsaur, France, in 1820.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] He went to Bolivia, and acquired mining interests there.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] Eyraud entered the Picpus Fathers as a novice.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] Influenced by his brother Jean, a missionary in China, he left Chile for Tahiti in 1862 and arrived at Hanga Roa on 2 January 1864.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] He was harassed by the islanders, and only stayed nine months before being repatriated to Chile on 11 October 1864.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] A year and a half later, on 27 March 1866, he settled on the island, accompanied by Père Hippolyte Roussel Ss.Cc. and three Mangarevan converts.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] Although fiercely opposed at first, Eyraud eventually came to be highly popular and influential among the islanders.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] In October 1866, Gaspar Zumbohm and Théodule Escolan joined Eyraud and Roussel in their mission, and set up schools at Hanga Roa and Vaihū.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] He assisted that year in what would be the last ceremony of the Birdman cult.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] Tuberculosis came to the island in 1867, which led to the death of a quarter of the island's population, and Eyraud died of it on 23 August 1868, nine days after the last islanders had been baptized.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] He was buried at the Holy Cross Church, Hanga Roa.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] During his first stay, Eyraud remarked that in each house there were wooden tablets covered with "hieroglyphs", now known as rongorongo, but that the islanders no longer knew how to read them and paid them scant attention.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] He didn't think of informing Roussel or Zumbohm, and never wrote of them again.
[src:alphonse-pinart/eugène-eyraud] In wasn't until 1869, when Zumbohm presented a gift which, unknown to him included a tablet, to Bishop Jaussen in Tahiti, that rongorongo was noticed by the outside world.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The **Exposition Universelle of 1867** (French pronunciation: [ɛkspozisjɔ̃ ynivɛʁsɛl]), better known in English as the **1867 Paris Exposition**, was a world's fair held in Paris, France, from 1 April to 3 November 1867.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] It was the second of ten major expositions held in the city between 1855 and 1937.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] A number of nations were represented at the fair.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Following a decree of Emperor Napoleon III, the exposition was prepared as early as 1864, in the midst of the renovation of Paris, marking the culmination of the Second French Empire.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Visitors included Tsar Alexander II of Russia, a brother of the King William and Otto von Bismarck of Prussia, Prince Metternich and Franz Josef of Austria, Ottoman Sultan Abdülaziz, and the Khedive of Egypt Isma'il.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] In 1864, Napoleon III issued a decree stating that an international exposition should be held in Paris in 1867.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] A commission was appointed with Prince Jerome Napoleon as president, under whose direction the preliminary work began.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The site chosen for the Exposition Universelle of 1867 was the Champ de Mars, the great military parade ground of Paris, which covered an area of 48 hectares and to which was added the island of Billancourt, of 21Ha.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The principal building was rectangular in shape with rounded ends, having a length of 490m and a width of 380m, and in the center was a pavilion surmounted by a dome and surrounded by a garden, 166m long and 56m wide, with a gallery built completely around it.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] In addition to the main building, there were nearly 100 smaller buildings on the grounds.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Victor Hugo, Alexandre Dumas, Ernest Renan, and Theophile Gautier all wrote publications to promote the event.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] There were 50,226 exhibitors, of whom 15,055 were from France and its colonies, 6176 from Great Britain and Ireland, 703 from the United States and a small contingent from Canada.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] In the "History of Work gallery", Jacques Boucher de Perthes, exhibited early prehistoric tools, the authenticity of which had just been recognised, in proof of his theories.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Napoléon III was particularly interested in exhibiting prototypes, designs, and models of workers' housing in the section of the exposition dedicated to workers' living conditions.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] He commissioned the architect Eugène Lacroix to design and build a set of four buildings on the rue de Monttessuy, at the edge of the exposition grounds, to demonstrate that affordable, decent housing for the working classes could be built at a profit.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The exhibition also included two prototypes of the much acclaimed and prize-winning hydrochronometer invented in 1867 by Gian Battista Embriaco, O.P.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] (Ceriana 1829 - Rome 1903), professor at the College of St.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] One of the Egyptian exhibits was designed by Auguste Mariette, and featured ancient Egyptian monuments.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The Suez Canal Company had an exhibit within the Egyptian exhibits, taking up two rooms at the event.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Which it used to sell bonds for funding.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The fair included a large ordnance section, showing improvements made in recent wars, in rifling, breechloading, and armored ships.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The huge naval guns that were exhibited drew a lot of attention.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The British government sent in a 30.5 cm (12.0 in) gun that weighed 23 tonnes.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The German manufacturer Krupp displayed a 35.5 cm (14.0 in) steel gun that weighed 50-tonnes.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] During the exhibition, the French government introduced a 42 cm (17 in) gun that weighed 38-tonnes.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Other nations that sent ordnance were: Austria, Belgium, Saxony, Holland, Egypt, and others.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Contemporary accounts, such as François Ducuing's *L'Exposition Universelle de 1867 Illustrée* (1867), provide detailed descriptions of the artillery exhibits in the Machinery Gallery.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The Prussian display featured a massive 50-tonne cast-steel breech-loading gun (35.5 cm calibre) manufactured by Friedrich Krupp of Essen.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Forged under a 50-tonne steam hammer and reinforced with steel hoops, it required a specially built 23-tonne railway wagon for transport to Paris.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Britain exhibited naval guns including a 9-inch (22.8 cm) Armstrong gun (12.5 tonnes) with an innovative recoil brake and loading cradle, as well as a Whitworth gun notable for its hexagonal rifling.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Sweden presented metallurgy from the Finspång works, including composite projectiles (hardened steel surface with cast-iron core) and heavy guns displayed in the park.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] France showed its new breech-loading naval artillery reinforced with hot-fitted steel hoops.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The largest piece was a 42 cm coast-defense gun weighing approximately 37–38 tonnes, capable of firing 300 kg projectiles to a range of about 7,800 metres.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] These displays illustrated the rapid progress in heavy steel artillery and breech-loading technology among European powers shortly before the Franco-Prussian War of 1870.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Americans displayed their latest telegraph technology and both Cyrus Field and Samuel Morse provided speeches.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] French explorer and early ethnobotanist Marie-Théophile Griffon du Bellay exhibited a display of dried specimens of some 450 species of useful plant, collected in the course of his recent explorations of Gabon and annotated with accounts of the uses to which they were put in their native land.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Griffon du Bellay was awarded two medals for his exhibit.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The exposition was formally opened on 1 April and closed on 31 October 1867, and was visited by 9,238,967 persons, including exhibitors and employees.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] This exposition was the greatest up to its time of all international expositions, both with respect to its extent and to the scope of its plan.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] For the first time Japan presented artwork to the world in a national pavilion, especially pieces from the Satsuma and Saga domains in Kyushu.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The Paris street near Champs de Mars, Rue de L'Exposition was named in homage to this 1867 universal exhibition.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] Jules Verne visited the exhibition in 1867 where he saw novel applications of electricity and a model of the French submarine Le Plongeur which inspired his electrically-powered Nautilus in *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] A famous revival of the ballet *Le Corsaire* was staged by the Ballet Master Joseph Mazilier in honor of the exhibition at the Théâtre Impérial de l'Opéra on 21 October 1867.
[src:alphonse-pinart/exposition-universelle-1867] The World Rowing Championships were held on the Seine River in July and was won by the underdog Canadian team from Saint John, New Brunswick which was quickly dubbed by the media as *The Paris Crew*.
